    "reasoning": "For Problem 1: The grid has 10 rows and 2 columns. The quantity w is the number of ways to mark one square in each of nine consecutive rows such that no two marked squares in adjacent rows share the same column. There are two choices for the set of nine consecutive rows: rows 1–9 or rows 2–10. For each set, choosing a column for the first row (2 choices) forces all subsequent columns to alternate due to the condition. Thus, each set gives 2 ways, so w = 2 × 2 = 4. Then e = w + 2019 = 4 + 2019 = 2023.\n\nFor Problem 2: We want to maximize L = n − m subject to the interval [m, n) containing more multiples of 2021 than multiples of 2000. The counts are A = floor((n−1)/2021) − floor((m−1)/2021) and B = floor((n−1)/2000) − floor((m−1)/2000). We need A > B. Using residues modulo 2000 and 2021 (which are coprime), the existence of m for a given L reduces to the condition floor((L+2019)/2021) > floor((L−1)/2000). Let k = floor((L−1)/2000). The condition implies L ≥ 2021k + 2, while k's definition gives L ≤ 2000k + 2000. Thus, 2021k + 2 ≤ 2000k + 2000, so k ≤ 95. The maximum L occurs at k = 95, where L can be as high as 2000×95 + 2000 = 192000. For L = 192000, we have floor((191999)/2000) = 95 and floor((194019)/2021) = 96, satisfying A > B. Larger L fail the condition, so the maximum is 192000.",
